</table></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#33333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub23.ezboard.com/ufraethir.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Fraethir</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Wizard</span><br>  Posts: 77<br> <font color=#ffffff>(3/17/02 7:23 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: .</span><hr size=1> Stick to what you've got, get what you've got fixed. When rogues were broken, well over half of their skills had no use or were broken, they couldn't tank, couldn't deal damage, had no purpose beside sucking up healing mana... They wanted to get fixed.<br>
<br>
They didn't get mend, or feign death, or able to wear plate armor (other class' perks). They got their broke-ass tools repaired. And in some cases, over repaired (and some things, like non stacking poisons and poison related issues, are still arguably broke).<br>
<br>
If VI addresses your summonables (making them useful instead of cute or 'naked-fear-break-only' items), and your pet drawbacks (not scaling past 49 terribly well, pathing AI, absolute non-desirability by MANY (but not all) others in many grouping situations, etc), you'll be better mages, and have less need/desire for lures (inefficient spells with lower resist chances).<br>
<br>
BTW: Your initial concept, I don't think works even in concept. EVERYTHING that isn't totally melee, melee ranged weapon based damage (weapon including things like feet, shields, or such), is non-melee damage. Falls are non-melee. Arrows are non-melee. nukes are non-melee, so are dots. Everything.<br>
I've always been pretty sure that's because Melee damage compares against armor mitigation, and nothing else does (or it'd be double jeapardy. Beat the resistance... then penetrate the armor. Yeah right). Your 'lure' idea of making it melee damage, but at range, breaks a lot of things. It makes it better than arrows, thrown weapons, and spells. All the advantages of not being in melee, with none of the downsides other than line of sight. Being 'melee' type damage, I bet it would even avoid the only-cast-in-melee range mobs, like fire giants. It's just not a good idea.<br>
All IMO, of course.<br>
<br>
By the way, Lures can and do get resisted. My first black reaver raid in City of Mist as a wizard, I was L51. So I was using Enticement of Flame. Inefficient, and slow. It stuck, roughly, 50% of the time. Sure, it beats bouncing totally 100% of the time, but it's not even all or nothing. It gets resisted, and you can still get partials. Lures, frankly, bite. But when the ONLY thing you can EVER do in combat is mana/magical based DD in one form or another, having even a lousy weapon beats having nothing at all that can touch an effectively magic (or fire/cold) immune critter.<br>
Take away a wizard's mana (or more accurately, their attack spells of DD/AoE/Rain) and they're reduced to a vastly inefficient melee with no special abilities, lousy weapons, and lousy skills.<br>
Take away a mage's equivalent spells, and they still have their utility function (granted, we can still evac/port, but that takes you OUT of the fight and does nothing to enhance staying IN the fight), the summoned items themselves if they apply, and two constant potential damage sources. Damage shields (utterly unresistable, damn them when they're on the mob), and pets. And even in bad pathing places, you could make of pets the same as lures, by casting them at the beginning of a fight, having them engage, and then reclaiming them at the end (or having them get lost). By summoning them next to the monster, few pathing issues. By banishing them after the fight, vastly less random risk of pathing trains. Yes, it IS incredibly mana inefficient compared to other methods... but so are lures. This kind of situational mana usage would be for when you don't think you have any other productive way to add to the fight (which is exactly when I use my lures. When there's nothing else I can usefully contribute to the group/raid by being there).<br>
<br>
YMMV<br>
Qwil, Kephra from the wizard side<br>
Sutekh from the melee side<br>
